{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"2cabb070-f78b-4759-b4f7-ff0bf8014fa1","content":"Here's how to collect a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app in a Windows container on Kubernetes:\n\n### 1. Exec into the container\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n### 2. Install `dotnet-trace` (if not already present)\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n```\n\n### 3. Find your process ID\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n### 4. Collect the trace\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio** or **PerfView**.\n\n### Getting the file off the container\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod-name>:<path-to-trace-file> ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n### Alternative: `dotnet-counters` for a quick look first\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-counters\ndotnet-counters monitor -p <PID> --counters System.Runtime\n```\nThis gives real-time CPU/GC/threadpool stats without a full trace — useful to narrow down the problem before collecting a heavier trace.\n\n> **Tip:** If `dotnet tool install` fails due to network restrictions in the container, you can copy the tools in via `kubectl cp` or bake them into your container image.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"28f6f629-ca2b-40f6-bc18-774cc542c6a7","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes, where they're experiencing high CPU. This is a diagnostic/troubleshooting question, not a code change request. I'll provide concise guidance.","outputTokens":418,"requestId":"C3D5:21BACA:1BDBC96:1F6E200:6A07C140"},"id":"a3f4d80c-a015-4f10-8bb6-57ff698addd5","timestamp":"2026-05-16T00:58:50.028Z","parentId":"e6823d0a-455c-48a2-81bb-a8863516e6c3"}
